hose within the village. Hesiod's Ascra directly counters the accepted view of Works and Days, which has Hesiod describing a peasant society subordinated to the economic and political control of an outside elite. Through his deft analysis, Edwards suggests a new understanding of both Works and Days and the social and economic organization of Hesiod's time and place.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aAgriculteursxBiographiesxGrèce. 0aAgriculture dans la littérature. 0aAgriculture in literature. 0aAscra (Grèce) dans la littérature. 0aBéotie (Grèce) dans la littérature. 0aDidactic poetry, GreekxHistory and criticism. 0aFarm life in literature. 0aFarmersxBiographyxGreece. 0aFarmerszGreecevBiography. 0aPoets, GreekvBiography. 0aPoets, GreekxBiography. 0aPoètes grecsxBiographies. 0aPoésie didactique grecquexHistoire et critique. 0aVie à la ferme dans la littérature. 0aVillages dans la littérature. 0aVillages in literature. 7aHISTORY / Ancient / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook Package 2000-2015z978311066334108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311069042240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520929579423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780520929579.jpg  a978-3-11-066334-1  UC Press eBook Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  a978-3-11-069042-2  UC Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles